WEBVTT

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.960
we see remarkable responses in ALL. So maybe I'm going to step back. So disease relapse is the

00:00:06.960 --> 00:00:12.780
leading cause of death after transplant. And actually, the data presented here are data from

00:00:12.780 --> 00:00:19.160
CIBMTR just a decade ago, where we saw that the majority of patients relapse post-transplant

00:00:19.160 --> 00:00:25.940
having ALL, and that was the main cause of death. So the question was, at that time, particularly

00:00:25.940 --> 00:00:31.240
as biological agents came along, is there something we can do about it? I mean, after

00:00:31.240 --> 00:00:37.060
transplant, so that we can modulate this outcome, particularly as post-transplant patients have low

00:00:37.060 --> 00:00:43.540
leukemia burden, donor T-cells are present, they were not exposed, maybe for tumor antigen,

00:00:43.660 --> 00:00:51.260
and can we prevent relapse? And so blenatumumab came along, obviously, first in relapse refractory

00:00:51.260 --> 00:00:55.900
setting. Now, many things have changed, and we are figuring out how to design,

00:00:55.940 --> 00:01:01.460
less toxic and most effective therapies for ALL. But kind of thought was that there are multiple

00:01:01.460 --> 00:01:08.400
mechanisms of immune evasion after transplant from checkpoint inhibitor upregulation, changes in

00:01:08.400 --> 00:01:16.260
microenvironment, novel mutations, but also downregulation of HLA class 2. And actually,

00:01:16.260 --> 00:01:23.020
on the right-hand side, I presume, of the slide, you can see some of the in vitro studies showing

00:01:23.020 --> 00:01:25.920
the upregulation of HLA class 2.

00:01:25.940 --> 00:01:32.320
Following treatment with blenatumumab, and also more efficacy in a lower angle of healthy donor

00:01:32.320 --> 00:01:39.960
T-cells, so providing in vitro tumor lysis and proliferation of T-cells in the context of

00:01:39.960 --> 00:01:46.880
blenatumumab. So we designed post-transplant blenatumumab study. As everyone knows,

00:01:47.060 --> 00:01:52.940
at Hopkins, we are very aggressive about non-myeloblative allogeneic transplant,

00:01:52.940 --> 00:01:55.820
and also the other part of our approach,

00:01:55.940 --> 00:02:01.420
post-transplant is to stop immune suppression very early on. So in generally, most of our patients

00:02:01.420 --> 00:02:06.860
stop immune suppression by day 60. So we felt maybe we can design a study where we are going

00:02:06.860 --> 00:02:14.420
to administer blenatumumab at the time as they complete immune suppression and by day 60 and try

00:02:14.420 --> 00:02:20.280
to really intervene at the time that most early relapses that are most detrimental occurred.

00:02:20.280 --> 00:02:25.920
So the study was designed, classical post-transplant side platform,

00:02:25.940 --> 00:02:32.620
and then patients were taken off immune suppression as a part of standard of care on day 60. They

00:02:32.620 --> 00:02:38.540
didn't have any evidence of GVHD, and the goal was to give one to two infusions, depending on

00:02:38.540 --> 00:02:46.440
MRD status determined by flow, within first 180 days post-transplant. And patients obviously could

00:02:46.440 --> 00:02:54.200
not have active GVHD requiring steroid therapy. So 57 patients were consented. We included ALL

00:02:54.200 --> 00:02:55.700
and non-Hodgkin lymphoma.

00:02:55.940 --> 00:03:02.720
This was more exploratory study. At that time, we didn't have all these affected biologic agents

00:03:02.720 --> 00:03:09.020
that we have these days for non-Hodgkin lymphoma. And 42 patients started treatment kind of half

00:03:09.020 --> 00:03:17.060
of lymphoma and leukemias. Main reason by screen failures were GVHD in those patients who needed

00:03:17.060 --> 00:03:25.280
some extra steroids or tacrolimus beat on day 60. And most patients completed one cycle of treatment.

00:03:25.280 --> 00:03:25.920
There were several

00:03:25.920 --> 00:03:31.100
patients that didn't complete because of transaminitis, neutropenia, patient preference,

00:03:31.100 --> 00:03:37.940
and one patient had early relapse. These are demographics. These are not CR1 just patient.

00:03:37.940 --> 00:03:43.980
I would say that majority of patients had more than two lines of therapy, two and more lines of

00:03:43.980 --> 00:03:51.200
therapy. Similarly for non-Hodgkin lymphoma, as well as for ALL. And some of them in non-Hodgkin

00:03:51.200 --> 00:03:54.620
lymphoma were in advanced CR3, 4, or PR.

00:03:55.900 --> 00:04:04.800
But what is important that among ALL patients, 68% did receive blenatumumab and also 10% of

00:04:04.800 --> 00:04:11.120
had prior allogeneic transplant. So this was second transplant. So this was bad group of patients. And

00:04:11.120 --> 00:04:19.720
there were also mutations associated with more aggressive diseases. So in terms of conditioning

00:04:19.720 --> 00:04:25.420
and transplant, majority of patients received reduced intensity conditioning and more than 70%

00:04:25.420 --> 00:04:25.880
of patients received less than 70% of patients received less than 70% of patients received less

00:04:25.880 --> 00:04:32.560
had haploidentical transplant, but more than half of patients were transplanted with PBSCT,

00:04:32.840 --> 00:04:39.300
with pH negative ALL, but for lymphoma, more commonly was bone marrow. What is important to

00:04:39.300 --> 00:04:46.420
say is that actually all patients were really able to start this treatment within 130 days,

00:04:46.540 --> 00:04:52.100
and practically they couldn't start before day 120 because by stopping immune suppression,

00:04:52.100 --> 00:04:56.660
allowing for a period of time that we had to monitor them before they can

00:04:56.660 --> 00:05:05.420
be enrolled on the study, this was the period. So I think this was relatively successful.

00:05:05.860 --> 00:05:12.120
In terms of toxicity, no major toxicities other than expected neutropenia in some of the patients,

00:05:12.260 --> 00:05:18.960
increased liver function tests, and just in the long term, there is always this question of

00:05:19.200 --> 00:05:21.960
oblinatumumab. Obviously, there was downregulation of immunoglobulin,

00:05:22.100 --> 00:05:27.260
there were approximately 25 patients where we monitored IgG and we ultimately replaced,

00:05:27.360 --> 00:05:30.880
but there was no infections or any adverse outcomes related to that.

00:05:31.320 --> 00:05:36.240
So these are the survival outcomes. This is at two years, but we have five-year follow-up,

00:05:36.360 --> 00:05:42.020
and actually we have 80 and plus more, almost 90% survival rate after two years,

00:05:42.020 --> 00:05:48.580
and relapse-free survival, actually I have three years, also has been in the range of 80%.

00:05:50.780 --> 00:05:51.380
So...

00:05:52.100 --> 00:05:58.960
Moving forward, the main relapses, and I think this is the most kind of coming recurring theme,

00:05:59.060 --> 00:06:05.340
what we are hearing here is that all three ALL patients who relapse on this study actually all

00:06:05.340 --> 00:06:13.660
relapse in central nervous system. There was no systemic relapses. And for several mental cell

00:06:13.660 --> 00:06:20.560
lymphoma relapse also, there were some with the CNS involvement. And they were early relapses,

00:06:20.640 --> 00:06:21.980
so I don't know that we can really...

00:06:22.100 --> 00:06:31.020
Say how much Blina could improve their outcomes. But in general, now what I'm showing you,

00:06:31.080 --> 00:06:38.100
we look recently in our outcomes for patients with ALL divided by the decades when the biologic

00:06:38.100 --> 00:06:44.520
agents and Blina tumor were approved versus not. And what we have and we compare in red

00:06:44.520 --> 00:06:51.920
is overall survival for the newer decade, and then blue is old decade,

00:06:52.100 --> 00:06:57.820
but we can see that there is in general overall survival in our patients with acute lymphoplastic

00:06:57.820 --> 00:07:05.060
leukemia post-transplant has been now 72%, relapse-free survival 65%. And actually,

00:07:05.180 --> 00:07:10.360
we transplanted sicker and older patients and works comorbidity index here, outcomes are

00:07:10.360 --> 00:07:15.880
improved. And I think the only what is attributable is the fact that these patients are now in better

00:07:16.160 --> 00:07:21.880
remissions. And this is now for CR1, how I think...

00:07:22.100 --> 00:07:29.720
It's another question, what about MRD? And if we are able to successfully eradicate MRD by Blina

00:07:29.720 --> 00:07:35.160
tumor these days, and we all give it to patients in CR1 and they go to transplant, these curves are

00:07:35.160 --> 00:07:44.700
pretty much getting close to 90% or something in terms of survival. So, I think this is small

00:07:44.700 --> 00:07:50.560
study. I think it cannot tell us that should we give to patient Blina tumor or not. And certainly,

00:07:50.560 --> 00:07:52.080
I don't have deep MRD.

00:07:52.100 --> 00:08:05.620
But I think overall, in designing the future, it's important to see that really these biological

00:08:05.620 --> 00:08:12.180
therapies are really eradicating MRD, which actually is transferring to improve outcomes

00:08:12.180 --> 00:08:18.460
also post-transplant. I think we will need to learn which patients should be transplanted,

00:08:18.460 --> 00:08:22.000
but it's really the pre-transplant therapy that is changing.

00:08:22.100 --> 00:08:26.700
What I can say for this study, that this post-transplant Blina was very

00:08:26.700 --> 00:08:32.620
feasible and safe. We didn't have any GVHD and did have very nice responses in our patients.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:39.660
This was not CR1 patients. So, future randomized trial, look at post-transplant Blina versus

00:08:39.660 --> 00:08:46.460
observation, but I would really like to look more in the role of MRD in deciding whether we should

00:08:46.460 --> 00:08:51.980
intervene. Maybe similar what we have now in AML in terms of FLT3 MRD.

00:08:52.100 --> 00:08:55.720
Anyway, thank you for having me here.
